'''Crossrail''' is a completed railway project centred on London. It provides a high-frequency hybrid commuter rail and rapid transit system known as the [[Elizabeth line]], that crosses the capital from suburbs on the west to east and connects two major railway lines terminating in London: the [[Great Western Main Line]] and the [[Great Eastern Main Line]]. The project was approved in 2007, and construction began in 2009 on the central section and connections to existing lines that became part of the route, which has been named the Elizabeth line in honour of Queen [[Elizabeth II]] who opened the line on 17 May 2022 during [[Platinum Jubilee of Elizabeth II|her Platinum Jubilee]]. The central section of the line between [[Paddington Station|Paddington]] and [[Abbey Wood railway station|Abbey Wood]] opened on 24 May 2022, with 12 trains per hour running in each direction through the core section in [[Central London]]. Crossrail is similar to the [[Réseau Express Régional|RER]] in Paris and the [[S-Bahn]] systems of German-speaking countries.<ref>{{Cite web| title=Crossrail project to Elizabeth line operations: Operational approach and lessons learned | url=https://learninglegacy.crossrail.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/Crossrail-project-to-Elizabeth-line-operations-Operational-approach-and-lessons-learned.pdf | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250606011951/https://learninglegacy.crossrail.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/Crossrail-project-to-Elizabeth-line-operations-Operational-approach-and-lessons-learned.pdf | archive-date=2025-06-06}}</ref>

The main feature of the project was the construction of a new railway line that runs underground from [[Paddington Station]] to a junction near Whitechapel. There it splits into a branch to {{stn|Stratford}}, where it joins the [[Great Eastern Main Line]]; and a branch to [[Abbey Wood railway station|Abbey Wood]] in southeast London.

When the Elizabeth line became fully operational in May 2023, the new nine-carriage [[British Rail Class 345|Class 345]] trains started to run at frequencies in the central section of up to 24 trains per hour in each direction through the central core, after which services divide into two branches: in the west to {{rws|Reading}} and to {{rws|Heathrow Central}}; in the east to {{rws|Abbey Wood}} and to {{rws|Shenfield}}. Local services on the section of the Great Eastern Main Line between {{stn|Liverpool Street}} and Shenfield had been transferred to [[TfL Rail]] in May 2015; TfL Rail also took over [[Heathrow Connect]] services in May 2018 and replaced some local services between Paddington and Reading in December 2019. The TfL Rail brand was discontinued when the core section of the Elizabeth line opened in May 2022.

The Elizabeth line's initial operating concession was awarded to [[MTR Corporation|MTR Corporation (Crossrail) Ltd]] as a [[London Rail]] [[Passenger rail franchising in Great Britain#Concessions|concession]] of [[Transport for London]] (TfL), in a similar manner to [[London Overground]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=18 July 2014 |title=TfL announces MTR to run Crossrail services |url=http://www.crossrail.co.uk/news/articles/tfl-announces-mtr-to-run-crossrail-services |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140722073117/http://www.crossrail.co.uk/news/articles/tfl-announces-mtr-to-run-crossrail-services |archive-date=22 July 2014 |access-date=2026-04-25 |website=Crossrail}}</ref> TfL's annual revenues<!-- including other operating income --> from the line were forecast in 2018 to be nearly £500{{nbsp}}million in 2022–23 and over £1{{nbsp}}billion from 2024 to 2025.

The total estimated cost rose from an initial budget of £14.8{{nbsp}}billion to a revised estimate of £18.9{{nbsp}}billion by May 2022.<ref name="wq">{{Cite web |title=Written questions and answers - Written questions, answers and statements - UK Parliament |url=https://questions-statements.parliament.uk/written-questions/detail/2022-05-16/hl242 |access-date=2026-06-04 |website=questions-statements.parliament.uk |language=en}}</ref> Originally planned to open in 2018, the project was repeatedly delayed, including several months caused by the [[COVID-19 pandemic in England|COVID-19 pandemic]].

Since the project was completed, '''Crossrail International''' continues to provide consulting services to other railway projects globally. [[Crossrail 2]], a proposed north-south line that would connect with the Elizabeth Line at [[Tottenham Court Road station]], was [[Safeguarding (planning law)|safeguarded]] in 2008 but shelved in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Wayback Machine |url=http://londonfirst.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/LF_CROSSRAIL2_REPORT_AW_Single_Pages.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130213150411/http://londonfirst.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/LF_CROSSRAIL2_REPORT_AW_Single_Pages.pdf |archive-date=2013-02-13 |access-date=2026-02-11 |website=londonfirst.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Hakimian |first=Rob |date=2025-03-20 |title=£1.1bn British Library extension to proceed with provision for future Crossrail 2 station |url=https://www.newcivilengineer.com/latest/1-1bn-british-library-extension-to-proceed-with-provision-for-future-crossrail-2-station-20-03-2025/ |access-date=2026-02-11 |website=New Civil Engineer |language=en}}</ref> 

